The three fisheries of WPP 712 and 713

Ernesto

March 1, 2018

This is the value table for WPP712 and WPP713 catches.

Species Weight Caught (kg) Weight Caught (%) Fish Value (IDR) Fish Value (%) Fish Value (cumulative %)
LP012 Pristipomoides multidens 112961 0.44 4.1e+09 0.39 0.39

SP003 Plectropomus leopardus 1313 0.01 3.9e+08 0.04 0.79

2 species make up 70% of the value earned, 5 species make up 80% it. The two most important species are Pristipomoides multidens and Lutjanus malabaricus However there is actually a negative correlation between malabaricus and multidens caught (as % of total landing). That is, it seems like people catch one or the other:

The correlation between the two is -0.33. On average we are missing 50% of all catches if we focus only on these two, and there about 16.55% of trips where neither of these two species are significantly landed.

In fact, lutjanus malabaricus (as a % of catch) is negatively correlated with all the other major species:

Lets try to cluster all these landings into a few categories to identify distinct fisheries.

The result is that we can basically cluster landings in three groups:

  1. Multidens heavy landings
  2. Malabaricus heavy landings
  3. Others

The top 5 species make up 60% of the abundance for the first two clusters, but cluster 3 is mostly unexplained:

Cluster Abundance explained by top species
1 0.67
2 0.63
3 0.24

Cluster 1, the multidens heavy fishery, involves large boats, while the other two clusters dont.

The other tell-tale difference is that most of cluster 2 fishing occurs in WPP 712, while cluster 1 and 3 fishing occurs in WPP 713.

The only mistery left is to figure out what is being caught in cluster 3. It turns out to be quite varied, but on average made up of the following:
